						<summary>

						<p>On a boulder in front of the natural cave called Āṇḍār-maḍam on the hill.</p>						

						<p>This record may be assigned to c. 8-9th century on palaeographical grounds.</p>						

						<p>It seems to record the gift of gold for a lamp in the <hi rend="italic">paḷḷi</hi> at Nandimaṅgalam and registers an undertaking given by Sembiyan Tamiḻavēḷar of the above <hi rend="italic">paḷḷi</hi> to the son of Tiruppūr-nakkaṉ of Pulaiyyūr to maintain the lamp by the female jaina acetic Kanaka vīrakkuṟattiyār and her pupils from out of the income from taxes like <hi rend="italic">eṇṇaik-kāṇam</hi> and <hi rend="italic">pudā-nāḻi</hi> granted by the latter. Nandimaṅgalam seems to be the other name of the Veḍāl, called Viḍāl, the findspot of the record. This name also figures in a record of Chōḷa Rājakēsarivarman discussed below. (No. 84).</p>						

						</summary>
